Lung cancer screening programs with computed tomography of the chest reduce 
mortality by more than 20%. Yet, they have not been implemented widely because 
of logistic and cost implications. Here, we sought to: (1) use real-life data to 
compare the outcomes and cost of lung cancer patients with treated medically or 
surgically in our region and (2) from this data, estimate the cost-benefit ratio 
